WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.888 --> 00:00:09.010
MALE SPEAKER: Good
afternoon and welcome to

00:00:09.010 --> 00:00:12.070
Talks at Google in
Cambridge, Massachusetts.

00:00:12.070 --> 00:00:16.510
Today it's my great pleasure
to introduce Gernot Wagner.

00:00:16.510 --> 00:00:19.300
Along with Martin
L. Weitzman, Gernot

00:00:19.300 --> 00:00:21.790
has co-authored the
subject of today's talk,

00:00:21.790 --> 00:00:25.710
"Climate Shock-- How Unnatural
Selection and Non-Random

00:00:25.710 --> 00:00:28.960
Mutation are Changing
Life on Earth."

00:00:28.960 --> 00:00:31.720
In the book they explore
the likely repercussions

00:00:31.720 --> 00:00:35.250
of a hotter planet
drawing on and expanding

00:00:35.250 --> 00:00:39.970
from work previously unavailable
to general audiences.

00:00:39.970 --> 00:00:43.530
They show that the longer we
wait to act the more likely

00:00:43.530 --> 00:00:45.970
an extreme event will happen.

00:00:45.970 --> 00:00:49.450
What we know about climate
change is alarming enough.

00:00:49.450 --> 00:00:51.970
What we don't know
about the extreme risks

00:00:51.970 --> 00:00:55.120
could be far more dangerous.

00:00:55.120 --> 00:00:56.540
They tell us that
we need to think

00:00:56.540 --> 00:00:58.710
about climate change
in the same way

00:00:58.710 --> 00:01:02.870
that we think about insurance,
as a risk management problem

00:01:02.870 --> 00:01:06.360
only here on a global scale.

00:01:06.360 --> 00:01:10.960
Gernot is lead senior economist
at Environmental Defense Fund,

00:01:10.960 --> 00:01:13.550
adjunct associate
professor at Columbia,

00:01:13.550 --> 00:01:16.590
and research associate at the
Kennedy School of Government

00:01:16.590 --> 00:01:17.850
at Harvard.

00:01:17.850 --> 00:01:20.671
Please join me in
welcoming Gernot Wagner.

00:01:20.671 --> 00:01:24.108
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:24.108 --> 00:01:25.310
GERNOT WAGNER: Thank you.

00:01:25.310 --> 00:01:29.210
Thank you, John, for
the kind introduction.

00:01:29.210 --> 00:01:32.680
I guess that big
question always is

00:01:32.680 --> 00:01:37.000
why yet another book
on climate change?

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:43.530
A topic that we all should know
quite a bit about, or at least

00:01:43.530 --> 00:01:45.315
know enough about to act.

00:01:45.315 --> 00:01:46.690
And the short
answer in this case

00:01:46.690 --> 00:01:48.390
is, this isn't
about what we know.

00:01:48.390 --> 00:01:51.400
It's about what we don't.

00:01:51.400 --> 00:01:54.070
And as John already mentioned in
the introduction, what we know

00:01:54.070 --> 00:01:58.880
is bad enough to lead
us to want to act.

00:01:58.880 --> 00:02:03.470
What we don't know is
potentially much, much worse.

00:02:03.470 --> 00:02:13.720
So here is a range of numbers
that basically defines life

00:02:13.720 --> 00:02:20.230
on earth, or will define life
on earth very, very soon.

00:02:20.230 --> 00:02:25.280
Now, turns out this
is 1.5 to 4.5 degrees

00:02:25.280 --> 00:02:28.000
centigrade, the number
of climate sensitivity,

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:30.700
which in fact only
really matters decades,

00:02:30.700 --> 00:02:31.840
centuries hence.

00:02:31.840 --> 00:02:36.910
It is what happens to global
average temperatures and both

00:02:36.910 --> 00:02:41.150
of these matter-- global
average-- as concentrations

00:02:41.150 --> 00:02:46.520
of CO2 in the atmosphere double.

00:02:46.520 --> 00:02:52.729
And what happens eventually
hundreds of years hence.

00:02:52.729 --> 00:02:54.020
Now, there's a few things here.

00:02:54.020 --> 00:02:57.700
Now, first of all, we've
already seen 0.8 degrees

00:02:57.700 --> 00:03:04.870
of warming centigrade since the
Industrial Revolution by today.

00:03:04.870 --> 00:03:06.500
So if you look at
this range and look

00:03:06.500 --> 00:03:09.600
at the lower bound
of this, 1.5, you

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:15.130
can be pretty sure that this
is in fact a lower bound.

00:03:15.130 --> 00:03:21.950
We you will be very, very lucky
if we undershoot that outcome.

00:03:21.950 --> 00:03:23.980
Now, there is a couple
more things here.

00:03:23.980 --> 00:03:26.987
So this has been
with us for a while.

00:03:26.987 --> 00:03:29.070
And frankly, this is really
the main point, that's

00:03:29.070 --> 00:03:33.860
the core point of this book.

00:03:33.860 --> 00:03:40.830
We happen to live in a world
where a range like this

00:03:40.830 --> 00:03:43.090
will define life on earth.

00:03:43.090 --> 00:03:51.540
And in about 35 years we have
learned very, very little.

00:03:51.540 --> 00:03:57.020
Now this is literally what came
out of a National Academy study

00:03:57.020 --> 00:04:01.032
by Jule Charney in 1979.

00:04:01.032 --> 00:04:01.990
And here's what he did.

00:04:01.990 --> 00:04:03.448
There were two
studies at the time.

00:04:03.448 --> 00:04:04.400
One said two degrees.

00:04:04.400 --> 00:04:06.380
The other one said four degrees.

00:04:06.380 --> 00:04:08.810
Add half a degree on each
side because why not?

00:04:08.810 --> 00:04:10.520
There's uncertainty after all.

00:04:10.520 --> 00:04:13.750
Average to two,
declare three degrees

00:04:13.750 --> 00:04:17.269
as the most likely value.

00:04:17.269 --> 00:04:20.050
And we were given this
range as something

00:04:20.050 --> 00:04:25.140
akin to a likely value.

00:04:25.140 --> 00:04:30.920
1990, IPCC, Intergovernmental
Panel on Climate Change,

00:04:30.920 --> 00:04:34.450
enshrines this range
as it's likely range

00:04:34.450 --> 00:04:36.320
for climate sensitivity.

00:04:36.320 --> 00:04:39.420
Decades of climate
research in between-- well

00:04:39.420 --> 00:04:41.640
technically, I guess 11
years of climate research

00:04:41.640 --> 00:04:46.140
in between-- many, many
years of improvements

00:04:46.140 --> 00:04:48.870
in how we understand and
amazing improvements in what we

00:04:48.870 --> 00:04:51.560
know about climate change.

00:04:51.560 --> 00:04:55.880
This key variable that
links concentrations

00:04:55.880 --> 00:05:00.870
to temperatures, what we
ultimately should care about,

00:05:00.870 --> 00:05:02.750
we don't know much more.

00:05:02.750 --> 00:05:05.820
1992, exactly the same.

00:05:05.820 --> 00:05:08.170
1995, once again.

00:05:08.170 --> 00:05:11.760
2001, we still have
precisely the same range.

00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:14.610
Now in the meantime,
what the IPCC has done

00:05:14.610 --> 00:05:18.360
is it has more precisely defined
what this range actually is.

00:05:18.360 --> 00:05:21.440
But now it calls it
the likely range.

00:05:21.440 --> 00:05:23.110
Not 67% likely.

00:05:23.110 --> 00:05:27.810
Turns out it's exactly
defined as 66%, so around 2/3.

00:05:27.810 --> 00:05:32.210
Don't ask why it's 66 not 67.

00:05:32.210 --> 00:05:37.210
But that is the probability
of being within that range.

00:05:37.210 --> 00:05:40.460
So by now we know
with greater certainty

00:05:40.460 --> 00:05:41.720
we'll be within this range.

00:05:41.720 --> 00:05:45.130
The range itself hasn't changed.

00:05:45.130 --> 00:05:50.060
Big revelation, 2007.

00:05:50.060 --> 00:05:52.720
Now two things happened.

00:05:52.720 --> 00:05:55.100
Well, one thing happened
to the range, the lower

00:05:55.100 --> 00:05:57.656
bound changed from 1.5 to 2.

00:05:57.656 --> 00:05:59.530
And now you have two
interpretations of this.

00:05:59.530 --> 00:06:03.210
One is to say, oh
good news for science.

00:06:03.210 --> 00:06:08.450
We now have a better idea
of what will in fact happen.

00:06:08.450 --> 00:06:12.300
It turns out it's bad
news for everybody else.

00:06:12.300 --> 00:06:15.050
Because it looks
like the lower bound

00:06:15.050 --> 00:06:16.690
is in fact, out at this point.

00:06:16.690 --> 00:06:19.900
Global average warming
due to a doubling of CO2

00:06:19.900 --> 00:06:21.530
in the atmosphere--
and double we

00:06:21.530 --> 00:06:25.610
will unless we change
course-- will now

00:06:25.610 --> 00:06:31.250
be at least 2 degrees centigrade
or 3.6 degrees Fahrenheit.

00:06:31.250 --> 00:06:35.020
That was 2007.

00:06:35.020 --> 00:06:39.750
Fast forward to October 2013.

00:06:39.750 --> 00:06:42.400
The latest and greatest
IPCC assessment

00:06:42.400 --> 00:06:46.240
report five, once again
hundreds of climate scientists,

00:06:46.240 --> 00:06:50.620
several years, lots and
lots of pages and dozens

00:06:50.620 --> 00:06:54.600
and dozens of academic
papers going into this.

00:06:54.600 --> 00:06:59.140
And apparently we are back
to where we started in 1979.

00:06:59.140 --> 00:07:02.290
1.5 to 4.5 degrees centigrade.

00:07:04.830 --> 00:07:07.330
Many, many years of climate
research, decades of learning

00:07:07.330 --> 00:07:12.470
and amazing advances in
climate research on basically

00:07:12.470 --> 00:07:18.940
most everything else, the one
defining number concentration

00:07:18.940 --> 00:07:23.570
of two temperatures, no change.

00:07:23.570 --> 00:07:28.430
That alone should already
give us pause at least,

00:07:28.430 --> 00:07:31.870
if not actively scare us.

00:07:31.870 --> 00:07:34.100
And of course, really
what's happening here

00:07:34.100 --> 00:07:37.570
is in this case you could sort
of reverse the 2007 argument

00:07:37.570 --> 00:07:40.360
and say, well, really
now what we can do

00:07:40.360 --> 00:07:41.980
is say, well, bad
news for science.

00:07:41.980 --> 00:07:46.080
Because we know less
apparently, up to a point.

00:07:46.080 --> 00:07:49.660
Good news for the
rest of us because it

00:07:49.660 --> 00:07:54.470
looks like lower global average
warming is once again part

00:07:54.470 --> 00:07:55.790
of the likely range.

00:07:55.790 --> 00:07:59.910
Well, turns out the uncertainty
itself, the risk itself,

00:07:59.910 --> 00:08:05.730
not knowing in itself is in
fact really, really costly.

00:08:05.730 --> 00:08:09.050
So this isn't good news
for the rest of us.

00:08:09.050 --> 00:08:11.450
It is in fact bad news for us.

00:08:11.450 --> 00:08:15.310
Having unlearned, well, for
that matter, taking into account

00:08:15.310 --> 00:08:17.970
this is not necessarily throwing
out the latest research.

00:08:17.970 --> 00:08:20.400
This is adding research
and saying, well,

00:08:20.400 --> 00:08:23.490
looks like taking
everything into account

00:08:23.490 --> 00:08:29.970
the range is indeed once again
higher than what we thought.

00:08:29.970 --> 00:08:33.559
OK, so here is another version
of the exact same story.

00:08:33.559 --> 00:08:37.890
So we could in fact look at a
probability density function

00:08:37.890 --> 00:08:41.390
essentially try to see what
is the chance of hitting

00:08:41.390 --> 00:08:44.770
every one of these global
average temperatures

00:08:44.770 --> 00:08:45.710
eventually?

00:08:45.710 --> 00:08:49.710
And there is a likely
range between 1.5 and 4.5.

00:08:49.710 --> 00:08:52.690
And yes, there is
a likely chance

00:08:52.690 --> 00:08:56.930
of being within that range, 66%
which by definition, of course,

00:08:56.930 --> 00:09:01.040
means it's unlikely we'll
be outside that range.

00:09:01.040 --> 00:09:03.740
But we can't ignore
the possibility.

00:09:03.740 --> 00:09:07.205
34% chance we will
be outside the range.

00:09:07.205 --> 00:09:08.580
Now, funny thing,
of course, when

00:09:08.580 --> 00:09:10.050
it comes to global
average warming.

00:09:10.050 --> 00:09:12.114
or global warming in general.

00:09:12.114 --> 00:09:14.280
We're pretty sure that
there's a lower cut off here.

00:09:14.280 --> 00:09:18.350
Adding CO2 isn't going
to lower temperatures.

00:09:18.350 --> 00:09:22.160
Or for that matter, where
we are today not even

00:09:22.160 --> 00:09:26.750
having increased
pre-industrial concentrations

00:09:26.750 --> 00:09:28.840
in the atmosphere
by as much as is

00:09:28.840 --> 00:09:31.900
necessary to get these
temperature outcomes eventually

00:09:31.900 --> 00:09:35.150
but only going from
280 parts per million

00:09:35.150 --> 00:09:41.700
pre-industrial levels to 400
today not yet 560, a doubling.

00:09:41.700 --> 00:09:46.160
Today we've already warmed
the earth on average

00:09:46.160 --> 00:09:49.510
by 0.8 degrees centigrade.

00:09:49.510 --> 00:09:52.280
In equilibrium, which is
really what this is showing,

00:09:52.280 --> 00:09:55.229
it will be higher
than today's value.

00:09:55.229 --> 00:09:57.020
And of course we haven't
stopped adding CO2

00:09:57.020 --> 00:10:00.630
into the atmosphere
in the meantime.

00:10:00.630 --> 00:10:05.290
So this is, in many ways, the
core of what's going on here.

00:10:05.290 --> 00:10:07.570
It's also slightly misleading.

00:10:07.570 --> 00:10:09.270
Because really what
we're doing here

00:10:09.270 --> 00:10:14.590
is just looking at what happens
every time you double CO2.

00:10:14.590 --> 00:10:17.980
Here is another view of this.

00:10:17.980 --> 00:10:21.520
International Energy Agency, you
take a conservative scenario--

00:10:21.520 --> 00:10:24.690
lowercase conservative
scenario-- of what is projected

00:10:24.690 --> 00:10:28.440
will happen by 2100 not even
not even eventually, basically

00:10:28.440 --> 00:10:33.350
this century, and we take
the number from the IEA

00:10:33.350 --> 00:10:37.270
that tells us 700
parts per million.

00:10:37.270 --> 00:10:40.912
They call this, by the way,
their new policy scenario.

00:10:40.912 --> 00:10:42.370
Or in other words,
they are already

00:10:42.370 --> 00:10:44.140
assuming that new
policies will come

00:10:44.140 --> 00:10:46.050
in place that are
currently not on the books

00:10:46.050 --> 00:10:48.420
or not projected to be
in place for that matter.

00:10:48.420 --> 00:10:51.290
But let's just give everyone
the benefit of the doubt.

00:10:51.290 --> 00:10:53.450
We will act.

00:10:53.450 --> 00:10:58.170
We will add new policies
despite that by 2100 we

00:10:58.170 --> 00:11:03.230
will be at 700 parts per million
of CO2 equivalent emissions

00:11:03.230 --> 00:11:03.980
in the atmosphere.

00:11:03.980 --> 00:11:08.480
So we have more than
doubled concentrations.

00:11:08.480 --> 00:11:11.040
What are the
temperature outcomes?

00:11:11.040 --> 00:11:17.160
Well, now we are
looking at a 10% chance

00:11:17.160 --> 00:11:19.250
of let's say,
temperatures exceeding

00:11:19.250 --> 00:11:24.840
six degrees centigrade,
11 degrees Fahrenheit.

00:11:24.840 --> 00:11:27.910
But this is, by definition,
on the unlikely side

00:11:27.910 --> 00:11:29.520
of our outcome.

00:11:29.520 --> 00:11:31.030
It's not what we expect to be.

00:11:31.030 --> 00:11:33.120
The expectation is lower.

00:11:33.120 --> 00:11:36.595
But of course we can't
exclude that a priori.

00:11:39.100 --> 00:11:42.140
Here's a slightly
different view of this.

00:11:42.140 --> 00:11:44.260
And of course the title
gives away the punch line.

00:11:47.500 --> 00:11:51.310
What everyone is focused
on, climate scientists,

00:11:51.310 --> 00:11:55.660
the IPCC Intergovernmental Panel
on Climate Change, everyone

00:11:55.660 --> 00:12:00.140
is focused on this top line.

00:12:00.140 --> 00:12:02.035
The median temperature
is the average.

00:12:04.710 --> 00:12:08.430
Today we are already at 400
parts per million for CO2

00:12:08.430 --> 00:12:08.930
alone.

00:12:08.930 --> 00:12:12.634
This is CO2 equivalent emissions
where we are about 450.

00:12:12.634 --> 00:12:14.430
Plus, minus a few.

00:12:14.430 --> 00:12:17.010
So we have basically
already locked

00:12:17.010 --> 00:12:23.160
in global average warming
off these 0.8 so degrees

00:12:23.160 --> 00:12:24.990
centigrade.

00:12:24.990 --> 00:12:27.590
And now we can consult
climate scientists

00:12:27.590 --> 00:12:29.980
and they will tell well,
there's a good reason

00:12:29.980 --> 00:12:32.770
we've chosen 2 degrees as
a threshold or some might

00:12:32.770 --> 00:12:34.417
disagree and say,
actually, really we

00:12:34.417 --> 00:12:36.250
ought to go back to be
pre-industrial levels

00:12:36.250 --> 00:12:38.840
and limit warming
to 1.5 degrees.

00:12:38.840 --> 00:12:41.410
Lots of debates to be had.

00:12:41.410 --> 00:12:45.790
What is non debatable is that
that global average will go up

00:12:45.790 --> 00:12:49.670
the more CO2 we add
to the atmosphere.

00:12:49.670 --> 00:12:52.180
And it'll go up by an
enough and of course,

00:12:52.180 --> 00:12:55.640
when you look at 700 PPM,
3.4 degrees centigrade

00:12:55.640 --> 00:12:58.920
of global average warming
is really, really bad.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:05.710
Just to give you
a sense of this,

00:13:05.710 --> 00:13:07.210
how it relates to
us today, well,

00:13:07.210 --> 00:13:11.570
today at 400 parts per
million we have, in fact,

00:13:11.570 --> 00:13:12.746
experienced this before.

00:13:12.746 --> 00:13:14.370
The planet has
experienced this before.

00:13:14.370 --> 00:13:16.200
We of course haven't.

00:13:16.200 --> 00:13:20.370
Last time that was the case was
more than 3 million years ago.

00:13:20.370 --> 00:13:28.110
Pliocene the geological
period and when

00:13:28.110 --> 00:13:31.030
you look at the record,
we had camels in Canada,

00:13:31.030 --> 00:13:32.530
crocodiles in Montana.

00:13:32.530 --> 00:13:36.350
Sea levels were up
to 60 feet higher

00:13:36.350 --> 00:13:40.600
than they are today, 20 meters
higher than they are today.

00:13:40.600 --> 00:13:44.170
Now, no one necessarily
predicts that this

00:13:44.170 --> 00:13:49.070
will in fact happen based
on today's concentrations.

00:13:49.070 --> 00:13:51.070
But of course, once again,
it points to the fact

00:13:51.070 --> 00:13:58.260
that we actually know a lot
less then we often think we do.

00:13:58.260 --> 00:14:03.530
And that not knowing
can only be costly.

00:14:03.530 --> 00:14:06.420
Now here is an even more
concrete manifestation

00:14:06.420 --> 00:14:07.850
of this how not
knowing is costly.

00:14:07.850 --> 00:14:08.850
Look at the bottom line.

00:14:13.010 --> 00:14:15.600
The median, the mean
goes up quite a bit.

00:14:15.600 --> 00:14:19.450
And that's costly and important.

00:14:19.450 --> 00:14:22.960
Now, no one would
disagree with six degrees

00:14:22.960 --> 00:14:24.930
average global warming.

00:14:24.930 --> 00:14:29.210
Which, by the way, means
polls of warming by at least

00:14:29.210 --> 00:14:30.980
around three times as much.

00:14:30.980 --> 00:14:33.140
So bad news for your
beachfront property.

00:14:33.140 --> 00:14:37.380
That's if you two degrees
of warming, let alone six.

00:14:37.380 --> 00:14:41.110
No one would disagree that this
is a planetary catastrophe.

00:14:41.110 --> 00:14:45.530
And look at the probabilities
of that happening

00:14:45.530 --> 00:14:50.230
as we creep up when it comes
to concentrations of CO2

00:14:50.230 --> 00:14:51.410
in the atmosphere.

00:14:51.410 --> 00:14:54.390
So right now we are
basically at around 0.3%

00:14:54.390 --> 00:14:58.010
which is not nothing.

00:14:58.010 --> 00:15:01.230
But at least it's less
than one in this case.

00:15:01.230 --> 00:15:07.610
Well, if you increase
concentrations from 450 to 550,

00:15:07.610 --> 00:15:10.660
which we will surely do
unless we take really,

00:15:10.660 --> 00:15:13.270
really strong
action, you've just

00:15:13.270 --> 00:15:17.500
increased the chance of global
average temperatures exceeding

00:15:17.500 --> 00:15:23.171
six degrees centigrade
by a factor of what?

00:15:23.171 --> 00:15:23.670
10X.

00:15:26.440 --> 00:15:30.840
That is huge.

00:15:30.840 --> 00:15:33.860
700 PPM you have a
probability of above 10%.

00:15:37.550 --> 00:15:42.550
We insure our houses, our lives,
our cars for a much, much lower

00:15:42.550 --> 00:15:43.451
probabilities.

00:15:43.451 --> 00:15:45.700
And of course, insurance has
a very particular meaning

00:15:45.700 --> 00:15:46.420
in that case.

00:15:46.420 --> 00:15:49.840
You pay an annual
premium in order

00:15:49.840 --> 00:15:52.510
for if that eventuality
in fact happens

00:15:52.510 --> 00:15:55.140
you get all your money back.

00:15:55.140 --> 00:15:57.840
In this case, there
is no such thing

00:15:57.840 --> 00:16:00.122
as insurance in
the sense of well,

00:16:00.122 --> 00:16:01.330
let's just wait what happens.

00:16:01.330 --> 00:16:04.680
If it's bad we'll
somehow make sure

00:16:04.680 --> 00:16:06.370
that we are made whole again.

00:16:06.370 --> 00:16:09.130
The only insurance
in this case, really,

00:16:09.130 --> 00:16:11.990
is putting the
price on CO2 today,

00:16:11.990 --> 00:16:15.780
avoiding emissions today.

00:16:15.780 --> 00:16:21.030
That's where the insurance
analogy comes to play.

00:16:21.030 --> 00:16:24.810
Now, so far I've told you
that what we care about

00:16:24.810 --> 00:16:27.200
is temperatures.

00:16:27.200 --> 00:16:29.410
Not the concentrations,
temperatures.

00:16:29.410 --> 00:16:33.680
And there's a lot of uncertainty
linking one to the other.

00:16:33.680 --> 00:16:35.380
It's not uncertain
that it'll be bad.

00:16:35.380 --> 00:16:39.430
It's just uncertain how
bad it will, in fact, be.

00:16:39.430 --> 00:16:44.280
Now really, we actually don't
care about temperatures either.

00:16:44.280 --> 00:16:46.900
You care about the
damages associated

00:16:46.900 --> 00:16:47.900
with those temperatures.

00:16:50.880 --> 00:16:53.850
If this wasn't
already scary enough,

00:16:53.850 --> 00:16:56.330
well, this is where
it gets really tricky.

00:16:56.330 --> 00:16:58.890
Because now we need
to make assumptions

00:16:58.890 --> 00:17:04.599
of what will happen in
terms of economic damages

00:17:04.599 --> 00:17:09.980
once global average warming
hits certain thresholds.

00:17:09.980 --> 00:17:12.860
And we've already
passed one degree.

00:17:12.860 --> 00:17:14.859
Sorry, we have passed 0.8
degrees at this point.

00:17:14.859 --> 00:17:16.190
But we are closer
to one degrees.

00:17:16.190 --> 00:17:16.689
Right?

00:17:16.689 --> 00:17:19.176
So we can look at
actual experience.

00:17:19.176 --> 00:17:20.290
How much are hurricanes?

00:17:20.290 --> 00:17:21.206
How much are droughts?

00:17:21.206 --> 00:17:23.849
How much are anything that's
linked with global warming

00:17:23.849 --> 00:17:26.040
today already costing us today?

00:17:28.940 --> 00:17:35.140
And then of course, you can
look at many, many, many studies

00:17:35.140 --> 00:17:38.250
that are going to
project, are projecting

00:17:38.250 --> 00:17:41.170
what will happen as well, you
creep up just a little bit.

00:17:41.170 --> 00:17:44.730
From 1 to 1.2 or from
1 to 1.5 and so on.

00:17:44.730 --> 00:17:48.970
What happens at
relatively low levels?

00:17:48.970 --> 00:17:55.730
No one has any idea what the
actual damages are at let's say

00:17:55.730 --> 00:18:02.650
five or six degrees centigrade
of global average warming.

00:18:02.650 --> 00:18:04.670
Now, that doesn't stop
economists of course.

00:18:04.670 --> 00:18:04.840
Right?

00:18:04.840 --> 00:18:06.010
So what do economists do?

00:18:06.010 --> 00:18:07.880
Well, we somehow need
to make assumptions.

00:18:07.880 --> 00:18:10.980
We need to extrapolate
based on actual experience

00:18:10.980 --> 00:18:16.200
of projections of what we
do know into the unknown

00:18:16.200 --> 00:18:19.940
or I would argue in
many ways unknowable.

00:18:19.940 --> 00:18:23.740
Well, when you look at the
standard assumptions feeding

00:18:23.740 --> 00:18:29.980
into the three models that
are used most prominently

00:18:29.980 --> 00:18:35.000
to calculate what climate
change is actually costing us

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:37.150
every single one of
them assumes something

00:18:37.150 --> 00:18:41.536
akin to this bottom line here,
a quadratic extrapolation.

00:18:44.190 --> 00:18:45.550
What does that mean in English?

00:18:45.550 --> 00:18:48.160
Well, no one really believes
it's a straight line

00:18:48.160 --> 00:18:51.490
as in the warmer it
gets we just keep adding

00:18:51.490 --> 00:18:53.770
sort of a bit of damages.

00:18:53.770 --> 00:18:55.860
Well, the warmer it gets
once you hit certain

00:18:55.860 --> 00:19:00.980
thresholds the higher the costs
of any additional warming.

00:19:00.980 --> 00:19:05.880
Hence not a straight line but
one that curves slightly up.

00:19:05.880 --> 00:19:07.900
Now, of course we
don't in fact know how

00:19:07.900 --> 00:19:10.490
that line ought to look like.

00:19:10.490 --> 00:19:15.300
Whether this quadratic
extrapolation here is in fact

00:19:15.300 --> 00:19:17.330
correct.

00:19:17.330 --> 00:19:20.670
Now, we are not saying that
the red line here is anymore

00:19:20.670 --> 00:19:26.450
correct then the quadratic one,
the exponential extrapolation.

00:19:26.450 --> 00:19:29.300
The point is we just don't know.

00:19:29.300 --> 00:19:34.250
What we do know is that
this quadratic extrapolation

00:19:34.250 --> 00:19:37.000
is in fact rather conservative.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:40.980
Very, very conservative,
lowercase conservative

00:19:40.980 --> 00:19:44.700
when you try to estimate
what the actual damages are.

00:19:44.700 --> 00:19:46.410
And the difference
is, in fact, dramatic.

00:19:46.410 --> 00:19:48.570
At one degrees or four
degrees, well, in fact,

00:19:48.570 --> 00:19:49.720
they're exactly the same.

00:19:49.720 --> 00:19:51.550
There is no difference.

00:19:51.550 --> 00:19:56.960
At six degrees, this is looking
at average global damages

00:19:56.960 --> 00:20:00.020
as a percent of global
economic output.

00:20:00.020 --> 00:20:02.280
You're now looking at a
difference between 10 and 30%.

00:20:04.900 --> 00:20:08.107
Those numbers are a trillion
here, trillion there.

00:20:08.107 --> 00:20:09.690
Soon enough you're
talking real bucks.

00:20:09.690 --> 00:20:13.060
So this starts adding up here.

00:20:13.060 --> 00:20:15.440
And once again, lots
of uncertainty what it

00:20:15.440 --> 00:20:16.600
actually is.

00:20:16.600 --> 00:20:18.100
We can be pretty
sure it's not going

00:20:18.100 --> 00:20:19.210
to be below the blue line.

00:20:19.210 --> 00:20:21.079
Although of course,
that is uncertain too.

00:20:21.079 --> 00:20:22.620
What, of course,
should really scares

00:20:22.620 --> 00:20:24.690
us is that there's
a potential to have

00:20:24.690 --> 00:20:27.400
this go quite a bit higher.

00:20:30.735 --> 00:20:36.360
OK, now here's what we
know-- or at least what

00:20:36.360 --> 00:20:39.650
the models that have the
known knowns and some

00:20:39.650 --> 00:20:41.680
of the known unknowns
and footnote somewhere.

00:20:41.680 --> 00:20:44.650
But certainly none of the
stuff that it could potentially

00:20:44.650 --> 00:20:50.520
really cost us big time--
those three economic models

00:20:50.520 --> 00:20:53.660
climate economic models
that essentially look

00:20:53.660 --> 00:21:00.190
at damages that we can
estimate grind the cranks,

00:21:00.190 --> 00:21:07.810
feed them through some pretty
sophisticated calculations,

00:21:07.810 --> 00:21:15.300
come up with $40 per
ton of CO2 as the cost.

00:21:15.300 --> 00:21:19.530
Now that's $40 per ton
of CO2 emitted today

00:21:19.530 --> 00:21:22.340
in today's dollars.

00:21:22.340 --> 00:21:25.450
That that ton of CO2, once
it's up in atmosphere,

00:21:25.450 --> 00:21:27.010
will cause over its lifetime.

00:21:27.010 --> 00:21:29.400
Stuff stays up there for
centuries, millennia.

00:21:32.130 --> 00:21:35.150
So much of the damage is
in fact in the future.

00:21:35.150 --> 00:21:36.820
Much of the damage
is in fact not

00:21:36.820 --> 00:21:42.887
affecting us but our
children or others children.

00:21:42.887 --> 00:21:44.720
Which of course, once
again, is the problem,

00:21:44.720 --> 00:21:48.130
why the global warming such a
big problem in the first place.

00:21:48.130 --> 00:21:50.830
Nevertheless, when you
calculate the cost of each ton

00:21:50.830 --> 00:21:57.097
you and I emit
today it's that $40.

00:21:57.097 --> 00:21:57.805
The known knowns.

00:22:00.520 --> 00:22:04.260
If you take the unknown
unknowns seriously,

00:22:04.260 --> 00:22:08.580
it's pretty clear that
